english:
  title: Record of the Deok-bang Inn
  author: Gwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Inns and hostels are established to receive travelers—to give rest to the weary, lodging to those who must stay the night. Through them, the rain finds shelter and the sun-scorched find shade. Bandits lose their terror, wild beasts their fangs. No greater blessing exists for merchants and wanderers. Thus do wise rulers cherish such places, and the Buddha's teaching likewise holds them sacred.

    Our kingdom honors those who maintain these sanctuaries, granting them fields and exempting them from corvée. Yet there are also those devoted to the dharma and goodness who, not content with building the inn alone, cultivate gardens beside it—offering vegetables to weary guests, fodder to their beasts. Such generosity returns manifold blessings.

    The Great Master Yeon, of the Divine Seal lineage, possessed a compassionate nature and boundless heart. His life was devoted to relieving suffering and benefiting all beings. In his twilight years, he settled in his native land—Gyerim itself—a place merely a hundred li from Ulju. All who traveled this road between distant places must rest here before continuing. Fish traders, salt merchants, garrison soldiers rotating their posts, horsemen, foot travelers, bearers and laden beasts—they came in endless procession. Yet without an inn, there was nowhere to shelter. Travelers crowded into villagers' homes, enduring the sweltering damp of summer rains and the piercing cold of winter snows. Both guests and hosts suffered greatly.

    Master Yeon resolved to build an inn at the midpoint of this road. He surveyed the land north of the path through Deok-bang Village—the great river flowing before it, bamboo groves rising behind, mountains embracing it, the ground itself level and welcoming. Pleased with what he found, he felled timber and fired brick. Work began in the winter of Gapsu and concluded in the autumn of Jeongchuk. Warm chambers and cool chambers were appointed separately, quarters arranged by rank. Kitchens and stables were made complete. He entrusted its keeping to his faithful disciples—diligent, conscientious, devoted to goodness. Summer brings fresh vegetables from their gardens; winter stores of kindling and fodder are laid by. Thus do man and beast receive sustenance year upon year, without end. In this, we see the boundless compassion of Master Yeon, how his virtue extends to all creatures.

    Though the distance be great, he has journeyed far to request that I record these deeds. How could I refuse to set brush to paper and gladly preserve his legacy?
  footnotes:
    - Gyerim (鷄林) is an ancient name for the Korean peninsula, particularly associated with the Silla kingdom region.
    - The dates given—Gapsu (甲戌) winter to Jeongchuk (丁丑) autumn—span approximately three years of construction.
    - The 'Divine Seal lineage' (神印宗) refers to a Buddhist transmission line, indicating Master Yeon's position within the monastic hierarchy.
